===Etymology 2===
From {{inh|en|enm|bold}}, {{m|enm|bald}}, {{m|enm|beald}}, from {{inh|en|ang|bald}}, {{m|ang|beald|t=bold, brave, confident, strong, of good courage, presumptuous, impudent}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*balþaz|t=strong, bold}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*bʰel-}}, {{m|ine-pro|*bʰlē-|t=to bloat, swell, bubble}}. Cognate with {{cog|nl|boud||bold, courageous, fearless}}, {{cog|gmh|balt||bold}} (whence {{cog|de|bald||soon}}), {{cog|sv|båld||bold, dauntless}}. Perhaps related to Albanian {{m|sq|ballë||forehead}} and Old Prussian {{m|prg|balo||forehead}}. For semantic development compare Italian {{m|it|affrontare||to face, to deal with}}, {{m|it|sfrontato||bold,daring, insolent}}, both from Latin {{m|la|frons||forehead}}.

